      <div class="card">
        <h3>What's Driving the Power Surge?</h3>
        <hr />
        <p>Texas is being reshaped by a wave of AI and industrial expansion that goes far beyond electricity demand. Tech companies are buying land at unprecedented speed, building massive campuses, and triggering new strains on water systems, cooling resources, and local infrastructure. Development is moving faster than public oversight, leaving communities to navigate consequences.</p>
        <a href="/stay-informed" class="learn-more">Learn more →Stay Informed</a>
        <ul>
          <li>Rapid expansion of AI and cloud data center campuses</li>
          <li>Massive land acquisitions by tech companies across Texas</li>
          <li>New industrial facilities reshaping local infrastructure needs</li>
          <li>Rising demand for water, cooling, and transmission capacity</li>
          <li>Construction of high-load sites outpacing regional planning</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>AI Data Centers in Texas.</h3>
        <hr />
        <p>Data centers are rising across Texas with little public visibility into their size, environmental impact, or long‑term footprint. From hyperscale AI campuses to high‑density compute sites, these facilities require enormous amounts of land, water, and construction resources. Companies are drawn by incentives and open space, but the true cost of this build‑out is only beginning to surface.</p>
        <a href="/stay-informed" class="learn-more">Learn more →Stay Informed</a>
        <ul>
          <li>Where major data center campuses are being built</li>
          <li>The companies driving Texas' data center boom</li>
          <li>How facility size, design, and cooling methods vary</li>
          <li>Water use, land impact, and environmental considerations</li>
          <li>Why Texas has become a national hub for AI infrastructure</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Texas Infrastructure Under Pressure.</h3>
        <hr />
        <p>The rapid construction of AI and industrial facilities is pushing Texas infrastructure to its limits. Water systems, wastewater capacity, road networks, and transmission corridors are being stretched by projects that often bypass traditional planning timelines. Cities are left scrambling to support growth they didn’t initiate — and in many cases, didn’t fully approve. This pressure is increasing.</p>
        <a href="/stay-informed" class="learn-more">Learn more →Stay Informed</a>
        <ul>
          <li>Strain on water systems, wastewater, and cooling resources</li>
          <li>Traffic, road wear, and heavy-equipment construction impacts</li>
          <li>Local permitting challenges and fast-tracked approvals</li>
          <li>Transmission lines, substations, and land-use conflicts</li>
          <li>Rising costs for cities supporting large industrial sites</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Impact on Texas Communities.</h3>
        <hr />
        <p>Residents in Texas are confronting the real‑world effects of large‑scale development: noise, traffic, water concerns, and the loss of open land. Tax incentives and fast‑tracked approvals often leave communities questioning who benefits and who pays the long‑term price. As more projects break ground, local pushback is growing — and so are the stakes. This trend is rapidly accelerating.</p>
        <a href="/stay-informed" class="learn-more">Learn more →Stay Informed</a>
        <ul>
          <li>Noise, traffic, and 24/7 construction near neighborhoods</li>
          <li>Water usage concerns and environmental trade-offs</li>
          <li>Loss of open land and changes to rural character</li>
          <li>Tax incentives vs. long-term community benefits</li>
          <li>Growing public pushback and local political battles</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
